	abstract = {As an ultrawide-bandgap semiconductor for extreme-environment applications, β-Ga<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub> exhibits remarkable radiation resistance. However, its behavior under extreme electron irradiation exceeding conventional energy regimes remains largely unexplored. Here, we combine 10 MeV electron irradiation (fluences: 1 × 10<sup>17</sup> and 5 × 10<sup>17</sup> cm<sup>−2</sup>), first principles calculation, and machine-learning molecular dynamics (ML-MD) simulations parameterized to match these conditions to systematically reveal the anisotropic structural limits and phase evolution mechanisms of β-Ga<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub>. Electron irradiation induces pronounced anisotropic lattice degradation, electronic and optical responses across different crystal planes (100), (010), (001), and (2¯01). The (100) plane undergoes severe near-surface degradation via the collapse of GaO<sub>4</sub> tetrahedra, evidenced by the disappearance of the B<sub>g</sub><sup>(2)</sup>, A<sub>g</sub><sup>(8)</sup> and A<sub>g</sub><sup>(9)</sup> Raman modes. For the (010) orientation, the pronounced channeling effect reduces scattering cross-sections and favors dispersed point defects, broadening the bulk X-ray diffraction (XRD) rocking curve full width at half maximum (FWHM) from ∼42 to over 155 arcsec. Across the four planes, irradiation induces a ∼690 nm infrared emission while differentially suppressing their intrinsic blue‑violet luminescence. The (001) plane demonstrates the highest overall tolerance. ML-MD simulations reveal that electron irradiation‑generated point defects reorganize into a low‑fraction, dispersed γ-phase inclusion that remains structurally coherent with the defective β‑phase matrix. These insights into the orientation-dependent structural, electronic, optical properties, and phase evolution establish a strategic framework for designing radiation-resistant β-Ga<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub> devices with sustained performance under extreme conditions. © 2026},
