	abstract = {Hydrodeoxygenation (HDO) is a vital process for upgrading lignin-derived phenolic compounds into high-value fuels and chemicals. This study develops a machine-learning framework to accurately predict phenol conversion and product selectivity (benzene, cyclohexane, cyclohexanol, and cyclohexanone) during catalytic HDO. A comprehensive dataset of 283 experimental points was compiled from the literature, incorporating catalyst properties (surface area, pore volume, pore size) and operating conditions (H<sub>2</sub> pressure, temperature, time, substrate ratios). Three algorithms, including support vector regression (SVR), gradient boosting regression (GBR), and Gaussian process regression (GPR), were compared. GPR outperformed SVR and GBR, achieving R<sup>2</sup> = 0.80–0.90, RMSE = 4.40–18.87, and MAE = 2.27–12.28 in the testing phase. Its superiority arises from its probabilistic Bayesian nature, effective handling of nonlinear relationships with limited data, inherent uncertainty quantification, and reduced overfitting risk through marginalization over hyperparameters rather than point estimates. SHapley Additive exPlanations analysis revealed catalyst pore size, H<sub>2</sub> pressure, and reaction time as the most influential factors for phenol conversion. The GPR-based model offers a robust, data-driven tool to guide catalyst design and process optimization for efficient lignin valorization. © 2026 Elsevier Ltd.},
