	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105037729839?origin=resultslist},
	affiliations = {Department of Safety Engineering/Fire Disaster Prevention Research Center, Incheon National University, 119 Academy-ro, Yeonsu-gu, Incheon, 22012, South Korea; Pricewaterhouse Coopers Consulting, 156 Gajeongbuk-ro, Seoul, Yongsan-gu, 04386, South Korea; Innovation Research Center for Zero-carbon Fuel Gas Turbine, Incheon National University, 119 Academy-ro, Yeonsu-gu, Incheon, 22012, South Korea},
	abstract = {Combustion instability, —influenced by co-firing ratios and combustor design—can pose serious challenges to turbine stability, efficiency, and safety. Moreover, the frequency of combustion instability has increased with the growing use of decarbonized fuels such as hydrogen. However, conventional sensor-based detection criteria lack adaptability and precision, especially when novel fuels are used. Machine-learning techniques—particularly long short-term memory networks and autoencoders—hold considerable promise for the analysis of complex data and, thus, the improvement of combustion instability detection and prediction. This research introduces a machine-learning-based diagnostic technique for detecting combustion instability in a hydrogen–natural gas co-firing gas turbine combustor. The proposed method employs machine learning to analyze subtle combustion instability patterns that can be challenging to detect with conventional approaches. By using long short-term memory networks and autoencoders, the proposed machine-learning method achieved substantially higher detection speed and accuracy than those of traditional techniques, including the root mean square, permutation entropy, and zero-crossing rate indicators. Moreover, at a reconstruction-error threshold, the proposed model outperforms the root mean square by reducing the detection time by 3.22 s and achieving ACCURACY and RECALL scores of 87.9% and 100%, respectively. These findings suggest that the proposed machine-learning technique can enhance the safety, reliability, and operational stability of hydrogen co-firing gas turbines by demonstrating adaptability to varying fuel compositions and combustor conditions, providing a highly reliable and efficient tool for real-time combustion instability management. Overall, this study enhances the robustness and resilience of combustion systems and contributes significantly to the development of safer, more efficient, and environmentally sustainable energy solutions. © 2026 Elsevier Ltd.},
