	abstract = {The development of accurate glucose monitoring techniques continues to present significant challenges in diabetes care, despite growing demand for alternatives to conventional invasive methods. This study explores the integration of multi-wavelength laser-based optical sensing and machine learning to improve the precision of glucose detection in aqueous solutions. The experimental framework employed laser sources emitting at four distinct wavelengths (405, 532, 673, and 833) selected based on their known interactions with glucose and potential to minimize interference from other biological components. Collimated transmission measurements were conducted to systematically evaluate how each wavelength responded to varying glucose concentrations. Among the tested wavelengths, 673 nm showed the highest accuracy, while 405 nm demonstrated strong consistency across data sets. In contrast, 532 nm and 833 nm required further optimization. To address the inherent complexities of spectral analysis, machine learning models were trained on extensive datasets derived from the optical measurements. These models effectively compensated for signal variability, enhanced prediction robustness, and accurately classified glucose concentrations in real-time. Moreover, the use of machine learning techniques allowed for improved prediction robustness, resulting in test accuracies of up to 94% at 673 nm. The results highlight the potential of combining advanced optical techniques with data-driven analysis to develop effective, user-friendly, non-invasive glucose monitoring systems, offering promising alternatives to traditional methods. Additionally, exploring further wavelengths in the near-infrared region and investigating advanced machine learning algorithms, such as ensemble learning or deep learning methods, will be pursued to enhance sensitivity and predictive accuracy, thereby improving the robustness of glucose monitoring in diverse biological. © The Author(s), under ex