	affiliations = {Department of Chemical and Petroleum Engineering, Khalifa University, Abu Dhabi, 127788, United Arab Emirates},
	abstract = {The wettability of rock/CO<sub>2</sub>/brine systems plays a critical role in controlling fluid distribution, capillary sealing, and trapping efficiency in geological carbon storage. This review provides a systematic and critical analysis of historical macroscopic contact angle datasets across a wide range of pressure, temperature, salinity, mineralogy, and organic content conditions. The compiled data indicate that increasing pressure generally raises contact angles, promoting CO<sub>2</sub>-wet conditions. In contrast, temperature effects are inconsistent and depend on mineralogy, interfacial properties, and experimental methods. Likewise, salinity, TOC, and surface chemistry produce complex, system-dependent wettability responses. A key contribution of this work is the reconciliation of these conflicting observations through a mechanistic framework that accounts for variations in surface roughness, fluid–fluid interfacial tension, chemical interactions, and measurement conditions. The review further integrates pore-scale observations from micro-CT imaging, molecular dynamics simulations, and machine learning models to establish a hierarchical, cross-scale interpretation of wettability behavior. This unified perspective highlights the limitations of relying solely on macroscopic contact angle measurements and emphasizes the importance of multi-scale coupling. In addition, the implications of wettability on capillary pressure, residual, dissolution, and mineralization trapping are critically examined to link interfacial phenomena with reservoir-scale performance and storage security. The analysis also identifies key limitations in current experimental datasets and predictive models, including inconsistencies in measurement protocols and potential overfitting in data-driven approaches. Finally, a structured research roadmap is proposed, prioritizing standardized experimental methodologies, physics-informed modeling, and integrated multi-scale investigations. These insights provide a more robust foundation for evaluating and optimizing CO<sub>2</sub> storage systems. © 2026 Elsevier Ltd.},
