	abstract = {Achieving a net-zero, sustainable, and affordable energy future requires cleaner and more efficient combustion processes powered by innovations in energy conversion technologies. Numerical simulations play a vital role in understanding combustion dynamics and enabling advancements in clean energy solutions. However, the trade-off between high fidelity and low computational cost remains a significant challenge, especially for models requiring direct integration of detailed chemistry, which demands substantial computational resources. This study introduces GPU-DNN and GPU-Seulex chemistry ODE solvers to accelerate reaction rate calculations. Simulations of the Cambridge stratified flame demonstrate good agreement between these GPU-based solvers and the conventional CPU-CVODE solver for flame statistics. The results reveal that the stratified flames are locally back-supported. This mechanism, driven by steep negative gradients of the equivalence ratio along the flame normal, extends the flammability limits and effectively mitigates the risk of local extinction. While the GPU-DNN solver is computationally more efficient, it struggles to precisely predict flame displacement speed in the burnout region due to difficulties in modeling minor rate changes near equilibrium. This limitation highlights the importance of evaluating DNN models not only for general flame statistics but also for local flame characteristics, especially in direct numerical simulations. Nevertheless, the significant speed-up offered by both GPU-DNN and GPU-Seulex solvers provides an encouraging foundation for detailed combustion simulations. This improved computational efficiency fosters a deeper understanding of combustion physics, paving the way for innovations in cleaner and sustainable energy technologies. © 2026 Elsevier Ltd.},
