	abstract = {Ammonia (NH<sub>3</sub>) is a promising carbon-free fuel for promoting energy transition, blending it with H<sub>2</sub> or CH<sub>4</sub> can improve low laminar burning velocity (LBV). However, the LBV of NH<sub>3</sub>/H<sub>2</sub>/air and NH<sub>3</sub>/CH<sub>4</sub>/air flames typically relies on 1D numerical simulations and experiments, which are costly and time-consuming. Therefore, it is necessary to develop machine learning (ML) models for predicting the LBV. Based on the experimental data from literature and 1D simulation data from validated kinetic mechanisms, two hybrid datasets were constructed. Four ML models were systematically evaluated, including MLP, RF, XGBoost, and SVR. The results indicated that XGBoost displayed excellent performance on both datasets after Bayesian optimization and 5-fold cross-validation, and the model remains reliable at high pressures, enabling reverse design of optimal conditions. Meanwhile, the extended Gulder LBV correlation was employed, and universal LBV correlations tailored to NH<sub>3</sub>/H<sub>2</sub> and NH<sub>3</sub>/CH<sub>4</sub> mixtures were established respectively by incorporating input parameters such as initial pressure, initial temperature, equivalence ratio, and H<sub>2</sub> or CH<sub>4</sub> mole fraction. The R<sup>2</sup> for both developed correlations exceeded 0.94, demonstrating high fitting accuracy. Moreover, dominant factors influencing LBV were identified via interpretable analysis (Shapley Additive exPlanations) of the prediction model, and the optimal parameter ranges corresponding to positive SHAP contributions (SHAP > 0) for LBV enhancement are determined as follows: NH<sub>3</sub>/H<sub>2</sub> mixtures: αH<sub>2</sub>≥ 0.53; φ = 0.92–1.48; T ≥ 415.74 K; P ≤ 4.58 atm·NH<sub>3</sub>/CH<sub>4</sub> mixtures: αCH<sub>4</sub>≥ 0.56; φ = 0.78–1.28; T ≥ 415.97 K; P ≤ 3.41 atm. Future work will expand the framework to NO <sub>x</sub> emission prediction. Copyright © 2026. Publi