	abstract = {Developing architectures capable of withstanding the synergistic coupling of extreme thermal, electromagnetic, and mechanical fields is a critical imperative. Decoupling the opposing functional requirements is more important compared to traditional manufacturing paradigms that are typically limited to single objective optimization. Inspired by natural geological chemical erosion processes, an erosion-guided design paradigm (EDP) that integrates machine learning (ML) with binder jet printing (BJP) is proposed to fabricate a geological-inspired microchannel cooling structure (GMCS). Mimicking natural erosion, continuous carbon fibers serve as sacrificial templates within a SiC matrix to generate directional microchannels. By identifying the critical channel dimension that balances specific surface area against flow resistance, the cooling efficiency is maximized without inducing choking. The decoupling of multi-field performance also realizes electromagnetic stealth under stable carrying capacity. To further clarify structure-property relationships, multiple ML models with experimental data are then assimilated into models to iteratively correct the algorithm, thereby reducing errors and enhancing the fidelity of the architecture correlation. Specifically, general regression neural networks (GRNN) were employed to map nonlinear geometric correlations, guiding the inverse design of optimal structure. The EDP provides a scalable pathway for developing next-generation multi-field stable materials for intelligent thermal protection and electromagnetic management. © 2026},
