	abstract = {Carbon dioxide (CO<sub>2</sub>) dissolution in formation water is a fundamental mechanism for secure, long-term geological storage. In Alberta, most current and planned sequestration projects target deep saline aquifers within basal Cambrian sandstones, which are geographically distant from major emission sources in the oilsands region. In contrast, shallower aquifers proximal to these sources have received limited attention due to concerns about leakage risks and potential interactions with potable groundwater. This study investigates the Lower Cretaceous Mannville Group as a proximal alternative by applying a three-step workflow integrating machine learning–assisted lithofacies classification, well-log interpretation, and petrophysical modeling to quantify dissolution-based storage capacity. Results indicate that the Mannville Group within 250–950 m depth is dominated by sandstone and siltstone (∼85%), with minor carbonate (∼2%) and shale (∼13%). The estimated mean water-trap storage intensity is 1.02 Mt/km<sup>2</sup> across the study area. The estimated in-place geological CO<sub>2</sub> storage potential is significant: 27.3 Gt for stacked sandstone aquifers and 50.1 Gt when sandstone and siltstone are combined, exceeding any other single trapping mechanism in the region. The findings demonstrate that dissolution trapping in the Mannville Group represents a major, underexplored opportunity for large-scale CO<sub>2</sub> storage adjacent to Alberta’s primary emission sources. However, while the theoretical in-place resource is vast, achieving significant dissolution via natural processes far exceeds typical project timescales. To materialize this capacity within a realistic timeframe, we propose using engineering innovations, such as active surface dissolution loops, to accelerate storage rates. Successfully deploying such solutions would not only support regional decarbonization and energy transition strategies in Alberta oilsands areas, but also e