	abstract = {Under high power density operation, the catalyst layer (CL) of fuel cells (FC) generates substantial heat. When heat transfer is limited due to a low effective thermal conductivity ( k <sub>eff</sub>), localized hot spots may develop, which in turn induce membrane dehydration and catalyst degradation, thereby significantly limiting the durability and performance of FC. Therefore, a systematic elucidation of the mechanisms by which the CL microstructure governs k <sub>eff</sub>, together with targeted microstructural optimization, is of critical importance for the large-scale deployment of FC technologies. In this work, a stochastic, realistic agglomerate-based microstructural model of the CL incorporating four distinct phases (platinum, carbon, ionomer, and pores) is reconstructed. A high-fidelity heat transfer model is developed and integrated with a machine-learning-based surrogate model and a genetic algorithm, thereby establishing a framework that is both computationally efficient and highly accurate for predicting and optimizing k <sub>eff</sub>. The results demonstrate that the ionomer volume fraction plays a dominant role in determining k <sub>eff</sub>, while the carbon phase enhances k <sub>eff</sub> mainly by improving the topological connectivity of the solid-phase skeleton. Meanwhile, the platinum phase locally enhances k <sub>eff</sub> through a ‘micro-thermal-bridge’ effect. Compared with conventional CL configurations, the optimized parameter set yields a 69.1% increase in k <sub>eff</sub>. These findings elucidate the thermal regulation mechanism associated with solid-phase network connectivity and provide theoretical guidance for the microstructural design of high-performance CL. © 2026 Elsevier Ltd.},
